1 the hands or mechanical apparatus of the scalp, face, neck, shoulders, hands,
2 and feet. Practices included within this subdivision shall not include the
3 practice of massage or bodywork therapy as set forth in Article 36 of Chapter
4 90 of the General Statutes.
5 (6) Cosmetic art school. – Any building or part thereof where cosmetic art is
6 taught.
7 (7) Cosmetic art shop. – Any building or part thereof where cosmetic art is
8 practiced for pay or reward, whether direct or indirect.
9 (8) Cosmetologist. – Any individual who is licensed to practice all parts of
10 cosmetic art.
11 (8a) Cosmetology. – The act of arranging, dressing, curling, waving, cleansing,
12 cutting, singeing, bleaching, coloring, or similar work upon the hair of a
13 person by any means, including the use of hands, mechanical or electrical
14 apparatus, or appliances or by use of cosmetic or chemical preparations or
15 antiseptics.
16 (9) Cosmetology teacher. – An individual licensed by the Board to teach all parts
17 of cosmetic art.
18 (10) Esthetician. – An individual licensed by the Board to practice only that part of
19 cosmetic art that constitutes skin care.
20 (11) Esthetician teacher. – An individual licensed by the Board to teach only that
21 part of cosmetic art that constitutes skin care.
22 (11a) Esthetics. – Refers to any of the following practices: giving facials; applying
23 makeup; performing skin care; removing superfluous hair from the body of a
24 person by use of creams, tweezers, or waxing; applying eyelashes to a person,
25 including the application of eyelash extensions, brow or lash color;
26 beautifying the face, neck, arms, or upper part of the human body by use of
27 cosmetic preparations, antiseptics, tonics, lotions, or creams; surface
28 manipulation in relation to skin care; or cleaning or stimulating the face, neck,
29 ears, arms, hands, bust, torso, legs, or feet of a person by means of hands,
30 devices, apparatus, or appliances along with the use of cosmetic preparations,
31 antiseptics, tonics, lotions, or creams.
32 (12) Manicuring. – The care and treatment of the fingernails, toenails, cuticles on
33 fingernails and toenails, and the hands and feet, including the decoration of
34 the fingernails and the application of nail extensions and artificial nails. The
35 term "manicuring" shall not include the treatment of pathologic conditions.
36 (13) Manicurist. – An individual licensed by the Board to practice only that part of
37 cosmetic art that constitutes manicuring.
38 (14) Manicurist teacher. – An individual licensed by the Board to teach
39 manicuring.
40 (14a) Natural hair care. – A service that results in tension on hair strands or roots by
41 twisting, wrapping, extending, or locking hair by hand or mechanical device.
42 For purposes of this definition, the phrase "natural hair care" shall include the
43 use of artificial or natural hair.
44 (14b) Natural hair care specialist. – An individual licensed by the Board to practice
45 only that part of cosmetic art that constitutes natural hair care.
46 (14c) Natural hair care teacher. – An individual licensed by the Board to teach
47 natural hair care.
48 (14d) Makeup artistry – The application of a cosmetic to enhance the appearance of
49 the face or skin using powder, foundation, rouge, eyeshadow, eyeliner,
50 mascara, or lipstick when providing no other services requiring a license under
